WEBVTT

0
00:00:00.209 --> 00:00:01.720
Welcome to The Explainer.

1
00:00:02.009 --> 00:00:02.329
You know,

2
00:00:02.569 --> 00:00:04.730
today we're going to get into something pretty powerful,

3
00:00:05.289 --> 00:00:06.150
project management.

4
00:00:06.449 --> 00:00:10.109
We're talking about the secret sauce that takes a huge ambitious idea

5
00:00:10.369 --> 00:00:12.170
and turns it into something real.

6
00:00:12.449 --> 00:00:13.810
Something you can actually build

7
00:00:14.050 --> 00:00:15.829
and do it on time and on budget.

8
00:00:16.430 --> 00:00:16.709
I mean,

9
00:00:16.790 --> 00:00:17.149
think about it.

10
00:00:17.270 --> 00:00:18.450
How do you build a skyscraper?

11
00:00:18.590 --> 00:00:20.350
How do you land a rover on Mars?

12
00:00:20.520 --> 00:00:20.790
Heck,

13
00:00:20.909 --> 00:00:23.690
how do you even launch a new website without it all falling apart?

14
00:00:23.909 --> 00:00:24.489
It can feel,

15
00:00:24.500 --> 00:00:24.780
you know,

16
00:00:24.870 --> 00:00:26.290
impossibly complex.

17
00:00:26.549 --> 00:00:27.299
But here's the thing,

18
00:00:27.469 --> 00:00:29.110
every single successful project,

19
00:00:29.229 --> 00:00:30.670
whether it's massive or tiny,

20
00:00:30.850 --> 00:00:33.110
is built on the exact same foundation,

21
00:00:33.229 --> 00:00:34.450
a rock solid plan.

22
00:00:34.700 --> 00:00:35.770
And that's what we're going to do today.

23
00:00:35.909 --> 00:00:38.009
Walk through the key ideas that make it all work.

24
00:00:38.310 --> 00:00:38.729
All right,

25
00:00:38.830 --> 00:00:40.299
so here's our game plan.

26
00:00:40.590 --> 00:00:40.959
First,

27
00:00:41.060 --> 00:00:43.619
we're going to figure out exactly what's in the box.

28
00:00:43.869 --> 00:00:45.630
What are we actually building?

29
00:00:46.229 --> 00:00:48.389
Then we'll get into creating the blueprint.

30
00:00:48.669 --> 00:00:49.110
After that,

31
00:00:49.189 --> 00:00:52.529
it's all about finding the fastest route from A to B.

32
00:00:52.930 --> 00:00:55.090
We'll look at how to visualize the whole thing,

33
00:00:55.279 --> 00:00:55.869
and finally,

34
00:00:55.970 --> 00:00:59.189
we'll talk about why all this planning actually matters.

35
00:00:59.549 --> 00:01:00.090
Sound good?

36
00:01:00.310 --> 00:01:01.029
Let's go.

37
00:01:01.389 --> 00:01:01.549
OK,

38
00:01:01.669 --> 00:01:02.270
first things first,

39
00:01:02.470 --> 00:01:05.220
before you lay a single brick or write a single line of code,

40
00:01:05.819 --> 00:01:08.339
everyone has to agree on exactly what is being built.

41
00:01:08.669 --> 00:01:08.910
I mean,

42
00:01:08.989 --> 00:01:10.010
you need clear boundaries,

43
00:01:10.099 --> 00:01:10.430
right?

44
00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:12.120
In the world of project management,

45
00:01:12.199 --> 00:01:14.059
we call this defining the scope.

46
00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:15.440
Let's use an analogy.

47
00:01:15.559 --> 00:01:16.739
Imagine you're building a house.

48
00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:19.550
The project scope is like the contract that says,

49
00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:19.940
OK,

50
00:01:20.239 --> 00:01:21.239
we're building a 2-story,

51
00:01:21.339 --> 00:01:22.580
3 bedroom house,

52
00:01:22.919 --> 00:01:23.389
but,

53
00:01:23.559 --> 00:01:25.419
and this part is just as important,

54
00:01:25.599 --> 00:01:28.660
it also says we are not doing the landscaping

55
00:01:28.660 --> 00:01:31.080
and we are definitely not building a swimming pool.

56
00:01:31.360 --> 00:01:31.680
See,

57
00:01:31.839 --> 00:01:33.919
it draws this really firm box around the work,

58
00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:35.919
so there's zero confusion down the line.

59
00:01:36.440 --> 00:01:38.319
And all of this gets written down in

60
00:01:38.319 --> 00:01:41.349
a formal document called a project scope statement.

61
00:01:41.559 --> 00:01:44.650
This thing is crucial because it gets literally everyone.

62
00:01:44.839 --> 00:01:45.919
We're talking the client,

63
00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:46.480
the team,

64
00:01:46.559 --> 00:01:49.099
the stakeholders all on the exact same page.

65
00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:49.919
And trust me,

66
00:01:50.089 --> 00:01:51.660
this isn't just boring paperwork.

67
00:01:51.830 --> 00:01:53.779
It's a powerful tool for alignment.

68
00:01:53.989 --> 00:01:56.519
It stops those costly misunderstandings before they even

69
00:01:56.519 --> 00:01:59.279
start and keeps the whole team laser focused.

70
00:02:00.010 --> 00:02:01.639
You know that clear box we talked about?

71
00:02:01.809 --> 00:02:03.650
It's your number one weapon against a

72
00:02:03.650 --> 00:02:06.730
really nasty project killer called scope creep.

73
00:02:06.889 --> 00:02:07.349
Oh yeah.

74
00:02:07.599 --> 00:02:08.970
This is when all those little,

75
00:02:09.169 --> 00:02:09.330
hey,

76
00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:12.210
can you just add this one thing requests start piling up?

77
00:02:12.610 --> 00:02:13.089
Before you know it,

78
00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:15.570
the schedule's a mess and the budget is totally blown.

79
00:02:15.850 --> 00:02:19.250
A good scope statement protects the project and let's be honest,

80
00:02:19.300 --> 00:02:21.690
it protects the team's sanity too.

81
00:02:22.190 --> 00:02:22.649
All right.

82
00:02:22.789 --> 00:02:24.500
So our scope is defined.

83
00:02:24.630 --> 00:02:26.649
We know exactly what we're building,

84
00:02:26.830 --> 00:02:27.449
but now

85
00:02:27.690 --> 00:02:30.460
how do we actually organize all the work that goes into it?

86
00:02:30.750 --> 00:02:31.669
We need a blueprint,

87
00:02:31.789 --> 00:02:32.089
right?

88
00:02:32.300 --> 00:02:33.169
A detailed one.

89
00:02:33.429 --> 00:02:33.899
And for that,

90
00:02:33.949 --> 00:02:37.889
we're going to turn to something called the work breakdown structure or WBS.

91
00:02:38.389 --> 00:02:38.669
Yeah,

92
00:02:38.759 --> 00:02:40.979
I know it sounds kind of formal and fancy,

93
00:02:41.229 --> 00:02:43.190
but a work breakdown structure is really just a

94
00:02:43.190 --> 00:02:45.449
powerful way of thinking about a simple idea.

95
00:02:45.710 --> 00:02:48.270
You take a huge goal and you chop it up into smaller,

96
00:02:48.380 --> 00:02:49.710
more manageable pieces.

97
00:02:50.100 --> 00:02:50.339
I mean,

98
00:02:50.419 --> 00:02:51.619
you don't just build a house,

99
00:02:51.699 --> 00:02:52.050
right?

100
00:02:52.300 --> 00:02:52.929
No way.

101
00:02:53.139 --> 00:02:54.199
You lay the foundation,

102
00:02:54.339 --> 00:02:55.410
then you frame the walls,

103
00:02:55.539 --> 00:02:56.660
then you install the plumbing.

104
00:02:56.929 --> 00:02:57.800
You get the idea

105
00:02:58.070 --> 00:03:00.119
and you can see how it all fits together

106
00:03:00.259 --> 00:03:01.130
like a pyramid.

107
00:03:01.300 --> 00:03:03.580
You start at the very top with your main goal.

108
00:03:03.820 --> 00:03:06.020
That gets broken down into major objectives

109
00:03:06.179 --> 00:03:09.160
and each of those objectives gets broken down into activities.

110
00:03:09.300 --> 00:03:10.179
And then finally,

111
00:03:10.419 --> 00:03:13.289
you get down to the specific individual tasks.

112
00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:17.139
It's basically a complete map of every single thing that needs to get done.

113
00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:18.029
Now,

114
00:03:18.039 --> 00:03:22.259
this whole idea brings us to the single most important principle of the WBS.

115
00:03:22.520 --> 00:03:23.919
It's a concept so critical,

116
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:25.580
it has its own golden rule.

117
00:03:25.919 --> 00:03:26.559
We call it

118
00:03:26.720 --> 00:03:28.100
the 100% rule.

119
00:03:28.759 --> 00:03:29.199
So,

120
00:03:29.479 --> 00:03:30.149
what is it?

121
00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:30.720
Well,

122
00:03:30.839 --> 00:03:33.460
the Project Management Institute puts it perfectly.

123
00:03:33.720 --> 00:03:37.119
The 100% rule basically says that your WBS has to

124
00:03:37.119 --> 00:03:40.529
include 100% of the work defined by the project's scope.

125
00:03:40.669 --> 00:03:43.009
It has to capture every single deliverable,

126
00:03:43.199 --> 00:03:44.440
and this is key,

127
00:03:44.639 --> 00:03:45.440
nothing extra.

128
00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:50.410
The sum of all the little pieces has to add up perfectly to the whole project.

129
00:03:50.699 --> 00:03:51.210
No more,

130
00:03:51.460 --> 00:03:52.160
no less.

131
00:03:52.570 --> 00:03:52.820
OK,

132
00:03:52.899 --> 00:03:56.080
so if you follow that pyramid all the way down to the bottom level,

133
00:03:56.259 --> 00:03:58.529
you find what we call work packages.

134
00:03:58.779 --> 00:04:00.100
Let's go back to our house example.

135
00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:02.919
A work package isn't something vague like do the kitchen.

136
00:04:03.309 --> 00:04:03.740
Nope.

137
00:04:03.940 --> 00:04:05.100
It's super specific,

138
00:04:05.339 --> 00:04:05.850
measurable,

139
00:04:05.860 --> 00:04:06.649
and assignable.

140
00:04:06.889 --> 00:04:10.160
It's a task like install all upper kitchen cabinets or

141
00:04:10.300 --> 00:04:11.460
connect the dishwasher plumbing,

142
00:04:11.660 --> 00:04:13.779
something you can actually hand off to someone to do.

143
00:04:14.500 --> 00:04:15.600
So let's recap.

144
00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:20.170
The WBS gives us a complete inventory of every single task we need to do.

145
00:04:20.420 --> 00:04:21.010
Awesome.

146
00:04:21.339 --> 00:04:21.779
But you know,

147
00:04:21.940 --> 00:04:23.820
just having a giant to do list isn't enough,

148
00:04:23.929 --> 00:04:24.290
right?

149
00:04:24.579 --> 00:04:26.459
The real magic comes from scheduling all those

150
00:04:26.459 --> 00:04:28.679
tasks in the most efficient way possible.

151
00:04:28.980 --> 00:04:29.609
And for that,

152
00:04:29.779 --> 00:04:31.920
we're going to need a really clever technique.

153
00:04:32.260 --> 00:04:32.609
I mean,

154
00:04:32.820 --> 00:04:33.690
that's the big question,

155
00:04:33.739 --> 00:04:34.140
isn't it?

156
00:04:34.339 --> 00:04:35.779
What order do you do things in?

157
00:04:36.190 --> 00:04:39.350
It's pretty obvious you can't put the roof on before you frame the walls.

158
00:04:39.519 --> 00:04:41.600
There are dependencies everywhere.

159
00:04:41.880 --> 00:04:42.040
Well,

160
00:04:42.119 --> 00:04:46.480
the critical path method is the technique we use to map out all those dependencies

161
00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:50.260
and find the absolute fastest route from the start of the project to the finish.

162
00:04:50.899 --> 00:04:52.829
And this isn't some newfangled idea.

163
00:04:53.019 --> 00:04:54.450
This technique is a heavyweight.

164
00:04:54.619 --> 00:04:56.489
It's been battle tested for decades.

165
00:04:56.700 --> 00:05:00.339
It was actually developed way back in the 1950s by giants like

166
00:05:00.339 --> 00:05:05.200
DuPont and Remington Rand to handle these insanely complex industrial projects,

167
00:05:05.420 --> 00:05:06.450
and right out of the gate,

168
00:05:06.500 --> 00:05:07.399
it proved its worth,

169
00:05:07.619 --> 00:05:10.500
saving tons of time and money in its very first applications.

170
00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:13.859
So here's the absolute key idea you need to get,

171
00:05:14.100 --> 00:05:15.250
the critical path.

172
00:05:15.489 --> 00:05:17.500
Think of it like the project's express lane.

173
00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:21.290
It's the single longest chain of tasks that all depend on each other

174
00:05:21.459 --> 00:05:23.250
from the very start to the very end,

175
00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:26.170
and the length of that one path determines the

176
00:05:26.170 --> 00:05:28.809
absolute minimum time your project can be completed in.

177
00:05:29.100 --> 00:05:29.739
Any delay,

178
00:05:29.890 --> 00:05:32.290
even a tiny one to a task on that path,

179
00:05:32.500 --> 00:05:32.660
well,

180
00:05:32.739 --> 00:05:35.329
it directly pushes back your entire project's finish date.

181
00:05:35.540 --> 00:05:36.109
No question.

182
00:05:36.470 --> 00:05:36.779
OK,

183
00:05:36.910 --> 00:05:39.309
I know this diagram might look a little complicated at first glance,

184
00:05:39.390 --> 00:05:40.190
but don't worry.

185
00:05:40.390 --> 00:05:40.970
All it is,

186
00:05:41.029 --> 00:05:41.570
is a map.

187
00:05:41.670 --> 00:05:42.190
That's it.

188
00:05:42.459 --> 00:05:43.929
Each one of those boxes is a task,

189
00:05:44.070 --> 00:05:48.410
and the arrows just show you which tasks have to be done before other ones can start.

190
00:05:48.709 --> 00:05:50.019
By mapping everything out like this,

191
00:05:50.149 --> 00:05:52.970
we can mathematically find that one longest,

192
00:05:53.230 --> 00:05:54.869
most important sequence of tasks,

193
00:05:54.989 --> 00:05:55.269
and that,

194
00:05:55.309 --> 00:05:55.790
my friends,

195
00:05:55.829 --> 00:05:57.010
is the critical path.

196
00:05:57.390 --> 00:05:57.500
So,

197
00:05:57.510 --> 00:05:58.260
any task that

198
00:05:58.424 --> 00:05:59.695
On that critical path,

199
00:05:59.945 --> 00:06:01.864
we call that a critical activity.

200
00:06:02.105 --> 00:06:03.315
And here's why it's so important.

201
00:06:03.584 --> 00:06:05.575
These tasks have zero slack,

202
00:06:05.804 --> 00:06:06.904
zero float.

203
00:06:07.105 --> 00:06:09.864
That means they have absolutely no wiggle room in the schedule,

204
00:06:09.984 --> 00:06:10.804
not even a day.

205
00:06:11.065 --> 00:06:11.214
Now,

206
00:06:11.225 --> 00:06:13.105
other tasks that aren't on the critical path,

207
00:06:13.265 --> 00:06:14.834
they might have a few days of slack,

208
00:06:15.105 --> 00:06:17.744
and this is huge because it tells the project manager

209
00:06:17.744 --> 00:06:19.924
exactly where they need to focus all their attention.

210
00:06:20.850 --> 00:06:24.760
So the critical path method is like the powerful engine under the hood,

211
00:06:24.970 --> 00:06:27.000
doing all the hard calculations for the schedule.

212
00:06:27.290 --> 00:06:29.130
But when you're actually driving the car,

213
00:06:29.250 --> 00:06:29.489
you know,

214
00:06:29.649 --> 00:06:30.929
tracking the project day to day,

215
00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:33.950
managers usually need something more visual on the dashboard.

216
00:06:34.670 --> 00:06:38.459
And that's where the difference between critical path and a Gantt chart comes in.

217
00:06:38.779 --> 00:06:39.869
Think of it like this.

218
00:06:40.109 --> 00:06:42.410
Critical path analysis is the calculation.

219
00:06:42.589 --> 00:06:44.160
It's the brains of the operation,

220
00:06:44.390 --> 00:06:47.329
figuring out that most important sequence and the project's end date.

221
00:06:47.589 --> 00:06:48.459
The Gantt chart,

222
00:06:48.709 --> 00:06:49.570
that's the visualization.

223
00:06:50.190 --> 00:06:53.500
It's a simple bar chart that plots all your tasks against a timeline.

224
00:06:53.709 --> 00:06:56.390
It's the dashboard that makes it super easy for the entire

225
00:06:56.390 --> 00:06:59.230
team to see what's happening and how things are progressing.

226
00:07:00.130 --> 00:07:01.410
So at this point,

227
00:07:01.489 --> 00:07:03.450
after talking about scope statements,

228
00:07:03.570 --> 00:07:04.410
work breakdowns,

229
00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:05.829
and all these diagrams,

230
00:07:06.010 --> 00:07:06.790
you might be thinking,

231
00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:07.609
wow,

232
00:07:07.769 --> 00:07:09.309
this seems like a lot of work

233
00:07:09.480 --> 00:07:10.239
and you're right.

234
00:07:10.529 --> 00:07:12.829
But why do we go through all this trouble?

235
00:07:13.049 --> 00:07:14.109
The answer is simple,

236
00:07:14.369 --> 00:07:16.809
because the payoff is absolutely enormous.

237
00:07:17.239 --> 00:07:19.149
And I'm not just talking in abstracts.

238
00:07:19.359 --> 00:07:20.829
Let's put a real number on it.

239
00:07:21.079 --> 00:07:24.619
Remember that very first real world test of the critical path method

240
00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:26.269
back at that DuPont plant?

241
00:07:26.519 --> 00:07:26.839
Well,

242
00:07:27.019 --> 00:07:27.720
by using it,

243
00:07:27.839 --> 00:07:31.820
they cut the unproductive shutdown time by 32 hours.

244
00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.549
It went from 125 hours all the way down to 93

245
00:07:35.760 --> 00:07:37.339
on just one project.

246
00:07:37.519 --> 00:07:40.799
You can imagine the kind of massive cost savings that translated to.

247
00:07:41.519 --> 00:07:42.670
So at the end of the day,

248
00:07:42.839 --> 00:07:44.269
what does all this planning get you?

249
00:07:44.470 --> 00:07:45.190
Two things,

250
00:07:45.679 --> 00:07:47.029
control and focus.

251
00:07:47.279 --> 00:07:48.459
That's the whole ballgame.

252
00:07:48.630 --> 00:07:49.540
It gives you a clear,

253
00:07:49.880 --> 00:07:51.100
undeniable roadmap.

254
00:07:51.239 --> 00:07:53.500
It means your team can spend their time and energy

255
00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:54.320
solving cool,

256
00:07:54.480 --> 00:07:57.510
creative problems instead of just constantly fighting fires.

257
00:07:57.720 --> 00:07:59.179
You know your earliest finish date,

258
00:07:59.320 --> 00:08:01.679
you know exactly which tasks can't slip,

259
00:08:01.910 --> 00:08:05.390
and you have a real baseline to measure your actual progress against.

260
00:08:05.559 --> 00:08:06.500
It's a game changer.

261
00:08:07.049 --> 00:08:07.489
But look,

262
00:08:07.630 --> 00:08:08.880
let's be real for a second.

263
00:08:09.119 --> 00:08:10.160
There's an old saying,

264
00:08:10.480 --> 00:08:13.260
no plan survives first contact with the enemy.

265
00:08:13.519 --> 00:08:14.459
And in project management,

266
00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:16.119
reality is the enemy.

267
00:08:16.440 --> 00:08:17.559
Materials get delayed,

268
00:08:17.679 --> 00:08:18.630
people get sick,

269
00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:19.799
unexpected problems,

270
00:08:19.880 --> 00:08:21.220
they always come up.

271
00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:23.640
A perfect plan is just the beginning.

272
00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:25.000
It's just the starting line.

273
00:08:25.279 --> 00:08:26.200
The real art,

274
00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:28.170
the real skill of project management

275
00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:31.559
is knowing how to adapt when things inevitably go sideways.

276
00:08:31.799 --> 00:08:34.039
